
[1]rough-cast

   ROUGH-CAST, v.t. ruf'-cast. [rough and cast.]

   1. To form in its first rudiments, without revision, correction and
   polish.

   2. To mold without nicety or elegance, or to form with asperities.

   3. To cover with a mixture of plaster and shells or pebbles; as, to
   rough-cast a building.

                          ROUGH-CAST, n. ruf'-cast.

   1. A rude model; the form of a thing in its first rudiments,
   unfinished.

   2. A plaster with a mixture of shells or pebbles, used for covering
   buildings.
